<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-279-816  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 279 816.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  March 19 1990 v9 n6 p54(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CECOM buys IntegrAda to develop Ada software. (the ArmyCommunications and Electronics Command acquires Aetech Inc.'sIntegrAda Ada Programming Support Environment)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taft, Darryl K.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Aetech Inc. (products).andO;Product:   IntegrAda (Program development software) (usage).andO;Topic:     ADAProgram Development ToolsAcquisitionApplications ProgrammingCommand and Control SystemsMilitaryGovernment AgencyUnited States. Army. Communications-Electronics Command.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>CECOM Buys IntegrAda to Develop Ada SoftwareandM;The Army Communications and Electronics Command (CECOM) has acquired a sitelicense for Aetech Inc.'s IntegrAda Ada Programming Support Environment, aCECOM official said.andM;CECOM purchased a site license for unlimited use of the Solana Beach, Calif.,andO;company's IntegrAda system throughout its headquarters at Fort Monmouth, N.J.andO;CECOM is the lead Army organization for developing command, control andcommunications systems and has spearheaded the Army's efforts in softwarereuse technologies and tools.andM;&quot;Our view is there is a lot of benefit in this thing.andP;  We view it as a goodvehicle for training and for developing small-scale applications,&quot; saidGeorge Summerall, head of the Software Engineering Technology Division inCECOM's Center for Software Engineering.andM;Summerall said CECOM's director of information management conducted anIntegrAda system evaluation and recommended the system be used.andM;&quot;We were interested in getting a product that would free our users to performcertain tasks, like editing and debugging, and developing small-scaleapplications, with the power available on their desktops rather than relyingon the mainframe,&quot; he said.andM;With the site license acquisition, CECOM will use IntegrAda throughout thecommand to develop Ada software that will run on the Army's minicomputers andmainframes as well as its microcomputers.andM;The IntegrAda system is an integrated Ada programming environment that runson the standard Army Z-248 from Zenith Data Systems Corp. and other Intelprocessor-based microcomputers.andP;  The product does not require extended memoryor math coprocessors.andM;The IntegrAda system includes a range of software development tools such aseditors and debuggers and a fully validated Ada compiler.andP;  Because IntegrAdahas been validated, source code developed using IntegrAda easily can beadapted to run on any other computer hosting a validated compiler, companyofficials said.andM;Aetech's IntegrAda also was selected recently as the standard MS-DOS Adacompiler for the Air Force's Desktop III, a $2 billion procurement for morethan 250,000 Unisys Corp. 80386 micros.andM;&quot;With these new acquisitions, there will be thousands of people usingIntegrAda,&quot; said Jim Thomes, president of Aetech and a past commander of AirForce computer training.andM;&quot;I expect this widespread usage will make IntegrAda a de facto standard forthe military, and Ada itself far more popular throughout the military, andAda itself more popular throughout the military-industrial community,&quot; hesaid.andO;</TEXT></DOC>